  "slug": "pithivier-almond-cream",
  "title": "Pithivier",
  "subtitle": "Round puff pastry pie filled with almond cream",
  "excerpt": "Two discs of puff pastry sealed around a rich almond cream, scored in a spiral pattern, and baked until puffed and lacquered with golden glaze. Serve warm. Serves 6 to 8.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The pithivier originates in the town of Pithiviers in the Loiret, France, where it is documented from the seventeenth century as a regional speciality. Auguste Escoffier, Le Guide Culinaire (1903), includes it among the standard puff pastry entremets. The form consists of two discs of puff pastry encasing a filling (traditionally almond cream or frangipane), with a crimped edge and a spiral scored on the top. It is closely related to the Galette des Rois baked for Epiphany.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The almond cream must be fully chilled before assembling, warm cream will soak through the pastry before it sets in the oven. Seal the edges firmly and chill the assembled disc before the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "pithivier scoring",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpa6nmbx0000s4v4cat3idj9"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": ". The glaze on top caramelises in the oven to give the lacquered finish.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
